IT HAS been 30 years since&nbsp;Mozambican president Samora Machel died but for his son, Samora Machel Junior, it feels as if it happened yesterday.&nbsp;Also read:&nbsp;MANDOZA 'ROBBED' FROM THE GRAVEMachel Junior addressed guests at an event to mark the 30th anniversary of his father&rsquo;s death and to unveil a monument in his memory in Mbuzini, Mpumalanga yesterday.&nbsp; Machel and 34 others died when their aeroplane crashed in the Lebombo Mountains between Swaziland and Mozambique.&nbsp; &ldquo;The 19th of October 1986 remains present in our memories, a memory left for us based on the principles of humility and respect,&rdquo; said Machel Junior.&nbsp; &ldquo;My family and the families of the 34 martyrs still feel the pain. We all lost a leader, a father, a son and a compatriot.&rdquo; The event was attended by deputy president Cyril Ramaphosa, Mozambican Prime Minister Carlos Agostinho do Rosario, Graca Machel and her children, Mpumalanga Premier David Mabuza and Mozambican officials.&nbsp; Ramaphosa said South Africa and Mozambique should continue building a solid relationship. He said the death of Machel 30 years ago created a bond tying the people of Mozambique and South Africa, which would never be broken.&nbsp;&ldquo;The struggle of building and developing our two countries must continue. We had a duty to fight apartheid and Machel died while he was bringing peace to Africa. He was a courageous man and hasinspired us to build a society free of discrimination. We need to ensure the lives of our people are better.&rdquo;